+Human Bein' Sigh. I had a really long reply that I wrote and it disappeared on me. Gonna try it again. The Bangles definitely were popular in the 80's but their image was mostly as a pop band and no one really knew how many hard rockers they had. 

But yes they weren't really revolutionary especially since their basis was off of the Paisely Underground which the movement's entire point was to take the sounds of the 60's and to modernize them. So in principle. their music wasn't revolutionary. But then again, being revolutionary can be overrated too. Big whoop if you make a totally different sound. If the sound isn't good, it isn't good. Sometimes just being the best amongst a popular genre is enough too.

I am now about to argue that Prince is both overrated and underrated. I am saying he is underrated because I as a young person never heard a song of his until after his death. He is one of the most famous artists of all time and many young people such as myself have overlooked him so I would argue that he is underrated. (Mostly due to his famous fighting against iTunes, YouTube and other digital music providers that he didn't want his music on which I can't blame him. Still guess what band I bought albums from and what artist that I have ignored thus far...)

I now am going to argue that he is overrated because I now have heard his supposed best song in Purple Rain. It was his performance during the Super Bowl halftime show. I don't get what's so special about it. In fact, it was kind of boring. How was it revolutionary? Granted, it was a live performance with what I would argue is poor quality, so I won't hold permanent judgement until  I buy the studio album and listen to it as Prince intended me to.

I watched the entire Super Bowl halftime show and was disinterested. I'm not calling him a bad songwriter. He wrote Manic Monday for crying out loud! I know he's talented! But I'm potentially arguing that he's an overrated performer. Or at the very least he gave a boring performance during the Super Bowl. Or the sound quality was just so horrid that it ruined all chance of me enjoying it.

My point in all of this is, it all comes down to an individual's opinion of the artist or band.
